          <text>
            I spend the next two days talking to everyone.

            Not saying goodbye exactly—more like… examining what this place means, what they mean, and what I mean to them.

            Runner finds me first, emerging from underground where they've been working on some new resonance design.

            Runner asks, "Kira—can we talk?"

            I say, "Of course."

            Runner settles their vines into a comfortable position and says, "I've been thinking about when you leave—if you leave—and I wanted to say… you changed how I see myself."

            I ask, "How?"

            Runner says, "Before the battle I followed protocols—underground construction guidelines, standard network designs. Then you asked about my tactical intelligence, and Florence actually listened—made me realize I could contribute beyond just executing orders."

            I say, gesturing at the acoustic chambers, "You've created incredible things—art and function together."

            Runner's vines shift. "Because I learned that individual perspective has value—you helped me understand that. If you decide to go back to your people, I'll miss that—the way you see things differently and aren't afraid to share it. But I also understand that humans probably need other humans."

            I ask, "Do they, though?"

            Runner tilts thoughtfully. "I don't know—do you?"

            I admit, "I don't know either. That's what I'm trying to figure out."

            Runner says, "Whatever you choose—thank you for helping me find confidence in my own voice."

            Later, Velvet finds me in one of the spaces they created—comfortable seating, pleasant proportions, designed with human needs in mind.

            Velvet shows me a new growth structure. It's beautiful—translucent layers creating light patterns, functional strength with artistic sensibility.

            I say honestly, "It's amazing."

            Velvet's growth rustles. "You taught me that beauty serves purpose. Before, I thought aesthetics were frivolous—function was what mattered. But you kept asking about how spaces feel, not just whether they're structurally sound—visual interest, comfortable proportions, pleasing textures."

            I touch the translucent growth as light filters through in complex patterns. "You already had the ability—I just asked questions."

            Velvet says, "Questions that made me think differently about what I create. The spaces we designed together are better because they consider human perspective alongside plant function. You contributed to that. Whatever you decide about the freighter, I want you to know—your voice shaped this community in ways that will last."

            My feedback helped create this. My voice mattered in its design.

            Remedy approaches while I'm examining the enhancement compounds they've developed—scents and colors and environmental improvements.

            Remedy says without preamble, "Chemistry can serve joy. I never understood that before you—science was survival: necessary compounds, emergency responses, protocol compliance."

            I ask, "What changed?"
          </text>
