        <chunk>
          <text>
            Remedy says, "You asked about human-safe fragrances—such a trivial question, I thought—but it made me realize chemistry could enhance life, not just preserve it."
            Remedy's edges shift with what might be satisfaction.
            Remedy continues, "Your questions challenged my assumptions about what I could create—made me a better scientist."

            I say, "You made my life better—these enhancements make this place comfortable, not just survivable."

            Remedy replies, "Exactly—comfortable matters as much as survivable. You taught me that."
            Remedy pauses.
            Remedy says, "If you leave, I'll miss your questions—they push me to think beyond protocol—but I also understand that humans might need human-appropriate environments more than plant-enhanced ones."

            ¶

            «Do I, though?»

            This plant-enhanced environment feels more like home than any human space I've lived in.

            Holloway finds me on the third day—wait, no, the second day—time is moving faster than I realize. The freighter arrives tomorrow.

            Holloway says, "Kira—We need to talk about your decision."

            I say, "I'm still thinking."

            Holloway says, "I know. But I want to make something clear."
            Holloway's bioluminescence brightens.
            Holloway continues, "You're part of this community—not as guest, not as temporary refugee—as an *actual* member whose voice shapes our collective direction. If you choose to stay, that's not charity or accommodation—it's us keeping someone we value."

            I ask, "And if I choose to leave?"

            Holloway says, "We'll be sad—Scout especially will be heartbroken—but we'll support it, because belonging means choosing to be here, not feeling trapped here."
            Holloway pauses.
            Holloway continues, "Whatever you decide, know that your voice mattered—you changed us and made us better at being a community that values individual contributions."

            I admit, "You changed me too."

            Holloway says, "Then we're even—make the choice that serves you, Kira—not what you think you should want, what you actually want."

            ¶

            «What I actually want.»

            «That's the core question.»

            On the evening of the second day, Florence approaches. I'm sitting in one of Velvet's comfortable spaces, Scout curled up beside me, thinking about tomorrow.

            Florence asks, "May I join you?"

            I say, "Please."

            Florence wheels into position.
            Florence says, "I owe you something."

            I ask, "What?"

            Florence says, "Perspective. When I was exiled, I believed redemption was impossible—that past mistakes defined me forever, that I'd always be the person who betrayed everyone's trust. You didn't accept that."

            I say, "I just asked you to help."

            Florence says, "You believed I could choose right action even when I doubted it—that belief changed everything. It gave me space to become someone who empowers rather than controls, someone whose present choices matter despite past failures."

            Florence's platform shifts.
            Florence continues, "Now you're facing a choice about who you are and where you belong—I want you to have the same freedom I did—to choose based on who you want to be, not who you think you should be."

            I say, "You think I should stay."
          </text>
