        <chunk>
          <text>
            Florence says, "I think you belong here. But that's different from *should.* Belonging only works if you choose it freely. Otherwise it's obligation, not authentic connection." 

            Florence pauses.

            Florence says, "When I helped out of exile, it was because I chose to. That choice mattered more than all the complex reasoning. You gave me freedom to choose. I'm giving you the same."

            I say, [softly], "Thank you."

            Florence says, "Whatever you decide, you changed my life. You gave me a chance at redemption I didn't think possible. That matters regardless of where you physically exist."

            Scout, who's been listening to all these conversations, finally demands full attention on the second evening.

            We're alone in my sleeping area—still mostly intact from before, though now enhanced by Remedy's comfortable scents and Velvet's soft moss improvements.

            Scout bounces—serious; needs to talk.

            Scout then says to me, "Are you going to leave?"

            I say, "I don't know yet. Maybe."

            Scout bounces—complicated. Scout says to Kira, "I'll be happy if you're happy—but I'll be heartbroken if you go. I want you to stay—but I want you to choose what's right for you. You're the best, you know that? I just love you—always will. Even if you go away."

            I say, "I love you too." Scout cuddles close.

            This tiny bouncing plant who adopted me immediately—who's provided unconditional affection and loyalty—sees me as family without complication or condition.

            If I leave, I'll miss Scout most of all.

            ¶

            «Buddy. Final analysis.»

            Buddy says, "Yes, Kira!"

            Buddy says, "All factors considered—psychological well-being in human civilization versus here; social integration; sense of purpose; authentic belonging. All of it."

            Buddy processes. "Quantitatively, your well-being indicators are significantly higher in the current plant community. You demonstrate greater purpose, deeper connections, more authentic belonging. Your individual voice has more impact on community decisions here than in any previous human environment."

            «So objectively, I should stay.»

            Buddy says, "Data suggests yes. But Kira, decision isn't just objective. It's about what you want your life to be—where you want your voice to matter."

            «What do I want?»

            «I think about returning to human civilization—finding a new courier job probably, or some other bureaucratic position. Functional existence among my own species. I'd have processed food again. Medical technology. Other humans to talk to about human things.»

            «But would any of them care about my individual perspective? Would my voice shape their decisions? Would I be Kira, or would I be employee number three thousand eight hundred forty-seven—a replaceable cog in an efficient machine?»

            «I think about staying here—this weird plant community where my human perspective genuinely matters; where my voice contributes to acoustic chambers and aesthetic design and enhancement chemistry and community decisions.»
          </text>
