          <text>
            Where I'm not just present—I'm valued. Where Scout loves me unconditionally. Where Florence found redemption partly because I believed in her. Where Runner discovered confidence, Velvet found artistic purpose, Remedy learned joy, Holloway leads by empowering. Where individual voices create a harmony richer than any protocol could design. The absurd irony is this—bureaucratic alien plants created a more authentic human community than humans did, because they value individual voices—including mine.

            I say to Scout, "I think I know what I want."
            Scout bounces—hopeful question.
            I say, "I want to stay."
            Scout explodes in happy bounces—joyful bounce, relief bounce, family-staying-together bounce!

            I say to Scout, "But I need to be sure—really, truly sure, because once I make this choice I'm committing to it."
            Scout bounces—understanding, take-time, be-certain, but hoping so hard.

            I sit with it—the decision.

            ¶

            Tomorrow the freighter arrives—the human rescue, return to civilization. Or—home: real home where my voice matters.

            The choice isn't actually hard. It should be—species loyalty, human connection, familiar culture; those things should matter. But what actually matters is being valued for who I am—contributing uniquely, having a voice that shapes the community I live in.

            Belonging. Real belonging.

            I tell Scout, "I'm sure—I'm staying here. This is home."
            Scout bounces the happiest bounce I've ever seen, then bounces a question—should I tell the freighter tonight?
            I say to Scout, "Tomorrow—when they arrive. I'll tell them in person that I'm choosing to stay."
            Scout bounces approval—proper choice, respectful.

            I ask, "You think so?"
            Scout bounces an emphatic yes—*they deserve to know I'm choosing freely,* not being held against my will—clear communication, human courtesy.
            I ask, "When did you get so wise?"
            Scout bounces modest—just common sense.

            I settle into my sleeping area—comfortable moss, pleasant scents, acoustic chambers humming gentle harmonics through the facility. Individual voices creating collective harmony—and my voice is part of that harmony now. Not a temporary visitor, not a protected refugee—part of the community. Home.

            Tomorrow I'll tell the freighter—thank them for coming but explain I'm staying. I've found a place here, a community that values me, a home that actually feels like home.

            They might think I'm crazy—a human choosing to live with alien plants instead of returning to civilization. But I know the truth: I'm choosing *belonging over familiarity*, authentic connection over demographic similarity, home over origin. My voice matters here in ways it never did before, in ways I didn't know were possible. That's worth more than any bureaucratic human system.

            Scout curls up beside me—content bounce, happy bounce, family bounce.

            Tomorrow the freighter arrives. Tomorrow I make my choice official.
          </text>
